5000|$|<b>The</b> Clayton <b>Antitrust</b> Act of 1914 ( [...] , codified at , [...] ), {{was a part}} of United States <b>antitrust</b> {{law with}} <b>the</b> goal of adding further {{substance}} to <b>the</b> U.S. <b>antitrust</b> law regime; <b>the</b> Clayton Act sought to prevent anticompetitive practices in their incipiency. That regime started with <b>the</b> Sherman <b>Antitrust</b> Act of 1890, the first Federal law outlawing practices considered harmful to consumers (monopolies, cartels, and trusts). The Clayton Act specified particular prohibited conduct, the three-level enforcement scheme, the exemptions, and the remedial measures.|$|R
